    "summary": "Keycloak exposes a tenant-hosted Admin REST API, OIDC/OAuth2 endpoint set, and Client Registration Service plus bundled `kcreg` CLI; authentication is primarily bearer access tokens, with client registration also accepting initial access tokens, registration access tokens, or HTTP Basic client credentials, while the public-client installation endpoint can be unauthenticated.",
    "credentials": {
      "kc_admin_bearer": {
        "type": "bearer",
        "label": "Keycloak bearer access token for admin or client-registration APIs",
        "setup": "Create a confidential client or use a user/service account in your Keycloak realm, then obtain an access token from the realm token endpoint described in the [OpenID Connect endpoints guide](https://www.keycloak.org/securing-apps/oidc-layers). For admin or client-registration access, grant the needed realm-management roles as described in [Using the client registration service](https://www.keycloak.org/securing-apps/client-registration#_authentication) and [Automating client registration with the CLI](https://www.keycloak.org/securing-apps/client-registration-cli)."
      },
      "kc_initial_access_token": {
        "type": "bearer",
        "label": "Keycloak initial access token",
        "generateUrl": "https://www.keycloak.org/securing-apps/client-registration#_authentication",
        "setup": "In the Admin Console for a realm, open **Clients** → **Initial access token**, click **Create**, optionally set expiration and client count limits, then copy the token value immediately; Keycloak only shows it once. Use it as `Authorization: bearer ...` for the client registration service as documented in [Using the client registration service](https://www.keycloak.org/securing-apps/client-registration#_authentication)."
      },
      "kc_client_basic": {
        "type": "basic",
        "label": "Keycloak confidential client ID and client secret",
        "generateUrl": "https://www.keycloak.org/securing-apps/client-registration-cli",
        "setup": "In your realm, create or open a confidential client and enable client authentication, then use the client ID and its secret from the client's **Credentials** tab. The client registration docs show this can be used with HTTP Basic auth for the installation provider, and the CLI guide shows passing the secret with `kcreg config credentials --secret`. See [Using the client registration service](https://www.keycloak.org/securing-apps/client-registration#_authentication) and [Automating client registration with the CLI](https://www.keycloak.org/securing-apps/client-registration-cli)."
      }
    },
